      <h2>The Short Answer</h2>
      <ul>
        <li>Social eating is the #1 consistency killer for men over 40 — not laziness, not lack of effort</li>
        <li><strong>Pre-load 15–20g of protein 30–60 min before social meals</strong> where options will be limited</li>
        <li>Anchor every plate around the highest-protein item available — steak, chicken, fish, eggs</li>
        <li>One low-protein meal won't hurt you; three or four a week will — so protect the week, not just the meal</li>
        <li>You don't need to announce your strategy. Invisible discipline beats performative restriction every time</li>
      </ul>
    </div>

    <!-- INTRO -->
    <p>I'm 64. I've been to more client dinners, backyard cookouts, and pizza nights than I can count. And for most of my life, I'd show up hungry, eat whatever was there, and think nothing of it.</p>

    <p>Then I started actually tracking my protein and discovered something uncomfortable: <strong>social meals were quietly destroying my weekly average.</strong> Not because I was overeating. Because the food available at most social situations — appetizers, pizza, chips, pasta, bread — is low in protein by default. You can eat a completely normal-seeming amount of food at a Friday-night dinner and walk away with 25g of protein.</p>

    <p>For men over 40, who need 30g per meal just to clear the anabolic threshold and trigger muscle protein synthesis, that's not a minor miss. That's a zero-protein meal dressed up as a full one.</p>

    <p>The answer isn't to stop socializing. It's to get smarter about the situations before they happen.</p>

