    <h2>Why Social Eating Hits Differently After 40</h2>

    <p>When you're 28, your muscles respond to protein stimulation more generously. Even a modest intake triggers some muscle protein synthesis. After 40, that sensitivity declines — a phenomenon called <a href="https://snapprotein.com/blog/anabolic-resistance-after-40/" style="color:var(--green);font-weight:600;">anabolic resistance</a>. Your body becomes more selective about when and how much it uses dietary protein for muscle repair and maintenance.</p>

    <p>The practical result: protein timing and dose matter more than they used to. A 20g protein meal that would have been adequate at 30 may not be enough to push past the threshold at 50. Social meals — which tend to trend low on protein and high on carbohydrates — become disproportionately costly.</p>

    <p>This isn't a reason to avoid them. It's a reason to build a strategy before you walk through the door.</p>

    <h2>The Pre-Load Strategy</h2>

    <p>The single highest-leverage habit I've found for social eating is pre-loading — eating a small, high-protein snack 30 to 60 minutes before a social meal where you expect limited protein options.</p>

    <p>Pre-loading does two things at once. First, it adds protein grams before the meal starts — so even a modest social dinner still contributes to a reasonable daily total. Second, it blunts appetite. When you arrive at a pizza night full instead of starving, you make calmer, more strategic choices. You're not grabbing three pieces in the first five minutes.</p>

