        </div>
        <div class="preload-item">
          <span class="preload-food">Hard-boiled eggs (2)</span>
          <span class="preload-g">12g</span>
        </div>
        <div class="preload-item">
          <span class="preload-food">Protein shake (quick mix)</span>
          <span class="preload-g">20–25g</span>
        </div>
        <div class="preload-item">
          <span class="preload-food">String cheese + jerky</span>
          <span class="preload-g">18–22g</span>
        </div>
        <div class="preload-item">
          <span class="preload-food">Tuna pouch (snack size)</span>
          <span class="preload-g">17g</span>
        </div>
      </div>
      <p class="preload-note">Each of these takes 3 minutes or less. None require cooking. All give you a 12–25g head start before you sit down.</p>
    </div>

    <h2>The Four Social Scenarios — and How to Navigate Each</h2>

    <p>Not all social eating situations are the same. A client steakhouse dinner is a very different problem than a backyard pizza cookout. Here's how to handle the four most common ones.</p>

    <div class="scenario-grid">

      <!-- Client Dinner -->
      <div class="scenario-card">
        <div class="scenario-header">
          <span class="scenario-title">The Client Dinner</span>
          <span class="scenario-badge badge-easy">Easiest to navigate</span>
        </div>
        <div class="scenario-body">
          <p class="scenario-problem">Nice restaurant, full menu, you're not the one choosing where to go — but you can choose what to order.</p>
          <ul class="scenario-moves">
            <li>Anchor your order around a protein entrée: steak, salmon, chicken, pork tenderloin</li>
            <li>Ask for double vegetables instead of a starch side — nobody notices, nobody cares</li>
            <li>Skip the bread basket or have one piece — not zero, just don't demolish it while you wait</li>
            <li>Order first if possible — it removes social pressure to mirror other orders</li>
          </ul>
          <div class="scenario-protein-note">6 oz sirloin = ~42g protein. Add a shrimp appetizer and you're clearing 55g before the entrée is finished.</div>
        </div>
      </div>

      <!-- Pizza Night -->
      <div class="scenario-card">
        <div class="scenario-header">
          <span class="scenario-title">The Pizza Night</span>
          <span class="scenario-badge badge-hard">Hardest to optimize</span>
        </div>
        <div class="scenario-body">
          <p class="scenario-problem">Friends' place, pizza delivery, beer, maybe wings if you're lucky. The protein ceiling here is real.</p>
          <ul class="scenario-moves">
            <li>Pre-load 20g before you arrive — this is non-negotiable for pizza nights</li>
            <li>Eat the pizza normally: 2–3 slices of meat-topped pizza = 20–25g, better than zero</li>
            <li>If wings are available, pivot hard — 6 wings with no sauce add 24g</li>
            <li>Don't restrict the rest of the day trying to "save room." Arrive pre-loaded instead</li>
          </ul>
          <div class="scenario-protein-note">Pre-load (20g) + wings (24g) + two slices (18g) = 62g. Manageable. Without wings or a pre-load, that same evening might land at 18g.</div>
        </div>
      </div>

      <!-- Backyard Cookout -->
      <div class="scenario-card">
        <div class="scenario-header">
          <span class="scenario-title">The Backyard Cookout</span>
          <span class="scenario-badge badge-medium">Moderate — depends on the grill</span>
        </div>
        <div class="scenario-body">
          <p class="scenario-problem">Burgers, brats, maybe chicken — but also chips, pasta salad, and potato salad competing for plate space.</p>
          <ul class="scenario-moves">
            <li>Make protein your first plate decision — load up on whatever is coming off the grill first</li>
            <li>Skip the bun on the second burger if you want the protein without the bulk</li>
            <li>Grilled chicken thighs are often sitting there ignored — 4 oz = 28g, grab two</li>
            <li>Pasta salad and chips are not competition — they're background. Treat them that way</li>
          </ul>
          <div class="scenario-protein-note">Two burgers (no bun, second one) + two chicken thighs = 70–80g. Cookouts are actually high-protein situations if you anchor to the grill.</div>
        </div>
      </div>

      <!-- Happy Hour -->
      <div class="scenario-card">
        <div class="scenario-header">
          <span class="scenario-title">Happy Hour / Bar Food</span>
          <span class="scenario-badge badge-hard">Low ceiling — plan around it</span>
        </div>
        <div class="scenario-body">
          <p class="scenario-problem">Wings, sliders, nachos, fried everything. Protein exists here, but it's diluted and calorie-dense.</p>
          <ul class="scenario-moves">
            <li>Pre-load before you go — bar food protein math rarely works in your favor</li>
            <li>Wings (unbreaded if possible) are the highest-ROI item — 6 naked wings = 24g</li>
            <li>Sliders: two beef sliders = roughly 18–22g, better than nachos but not a full meal</li>
            <li>Plan a high-protein dinner afterward rather than trying to make the bar food "count"</li>
          </ul>
          <div class="scenario-protein-note">Happy hour is the situation to not fight. Pre-load, enjoy the social time, eat a solid dinner after. That's the play.</div>
        </div>
      </div>

    </div>

    <h2>The Weekly Math Is What Actually Matters</h2>

    <p>Here's the mindset shift that changed how I approach social eating: <strong>one low-protein meal doesn't cause muscle loss. A pattern does.</strong></p>

    <p>Men over 40 who are professionally and socially active might have four or five social eating occasions in a week. If each one comes in at 20–30g instead of 40–50g, that's a 60–100g weekly deficit quietly accumulating beneath the surface. Multiply that across 52 weeks and you're looking at a chronic protein shortfall that compounds over time.</p>

    <p>The fix isn't perfection at every social meal. It's making your non-social meals non-negotiable so the math still works over the week — even if Thursday's pizza night was a wash.</p>

    <div class="week-math">
      <h3>A Realistic Week — With and Without Social Eating Strategy</h3>
      <div class="week-row">
        <span class="week-day">Monday (home)</span>
        <span class="week-g-good">128g ✓</span>
      </div>
      <div class="week-row">
        <span class="week-day">Tuesday (home)</span>
        <span class="week-g-good">122g ✓</span>
      </div>
      <div class="week-row">
        <span class="week-day">Wednesday (client dinner — anchored to steak)</span>
        <span class="week-g-good">115g ✓</span>
      </div>
      <div class="week-row">
        <span class="week-day">Thursday (pizza night — no pre-load, no strategy)</span>
        <span class="week-g-low">38g ✗</span>
      </div>
      <div class="week-row">
        <span class="week-day">Friday (cookout — anchored to grill)</span>
        <span class="week-g-good">110g ✓</span>
      </div>
      <div class="week-row">
        <span class="week-day">Saturday (home)</span>
        <span class="week-g-good">130g ✓</span>
      </div>
      <div class="week-row">
        <span class="week-day">Sunday (home)</span>
        <span class="week-g-good">125g ✓</span>
      </div>
      <div class="week-math-total">Weekly average: 767g ÷ 7 = 109g/day — one Thursday nearly tanked an otherwise strong week</div>
    </div>

    <p>Thursday was the unmanaged one. No pre-load, no strategy, arrived hungry. The rest of the week was strong. But notice how one bad social night pulled the weekly average down by nearly 10g per day. Now imagine that happening Tuesday <em>and</em> Thursday, every week.</p>

    <p>This is why visibility matters more than willpower. When you can see your number at the end of each day, the pattern becomes obvious. You can course-correct Thursday before it becomes every Thursday.</p>

    <h2>The Invisible Strategy Principle</h2>

    <p>The goal is never to be "that guy." The guy who asks the waiter about protein content. Who announces he's watching what he eats. Who makes his dietary choices the topic of conversation.</p>

    <p>Good social protein strategy is invisible. It looks like: arriving not starving. Ordering the steak. Asking for extra vegetables. Grabbing the wings first. None of those choices require explanation or announcement. They're just decisions — made quietly, consistently, without drawing attention.</p>

    <p>The only thing visible should be that you're enjoying the meal and the company. The strategy runs in the background.</p>

